   <h1>Re: [T2] Re: Lower L/H Ball Joint Removal</h1>
   <b>"Bill Harris" <biharris(-at-)cgmailbox.com></b><br/>
   <i>2002-05-16 23:03:37+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>After removing the clip, remove the stop.
----- Original Message -----
From: Bill Harris 
To: 
Sent: Thursday, May 16, 2002 4:02 PM
Subject: Re: [T2] Re: Lower L/H Ball Joint Removal


> Jack up the spindle so the upper arm is off the rubber stop.  Remove the
> clip holding the rubber stop on.  Lower the spindle.  Beat on the inside
of
> the arm and it will be off in under 10 blows (using a 4lb hammer!).  Then
it
> will slide right off.  Putting back on be sure the seal is properly
seated.
> Don't mangle as all my research shows they are currently NLA.
>
> Good luck,
> Bill
>
> ----- Original Message -----
> From: Larry Edson 
> To: 
> Sent: Thursday, May 16, 2002 4:05 PM
> Subject: [T2] Re: Lower L/H Ball Joint Removal
>
>
> > type2-digest-help(-at-)type2.com wrote:
> >
> > > Date: Thu, 16 May 2002 10:13:11 -0400 (EDT)
> > > From: andy 
> > > cc:  
> > > Subject: Re: [T2] Lower L/H Ball Joint Removal (?)
> > >
> > > > Sorry, I forgot you didn't already know what is was thinking...  I
> would
> > > > follow Bentley.  I wouldn't heat the trailing arm.  I would remove
the
> arm
> > > > myself (did a couple weeks ago).  I would try to remove it myself
> > > > (unsuccessfully).  I would take it with the new joint to a place
that
> knows
> > > > what their doing.
> > >
> > > Bus Boys has rebuilt trailing arms for 175 plus 50 for the cores.
> > > Just a thought if you plan to do all 4. I dont know if theyll swap
them
> > > individually.
> >
> > I'm in the midst of this same process on my '70 and having recently
> replaced ball joints on a Type 3 I thought I would have no problem.  Well,
> the first thing I found is that the upper control arm setup is different
and
> I can't figure out how to get it
> > out.  On the Type 3 all I had to do was take out a stop plate and the
> whole thing rotated up in the torsion tube and the drop arms slipped right
> out.  The Type 2 has tension against the rubber stops and I can't figure
how
> the drop arms come off.
> >
> > The second thing I found is that the same shop I took the Type 3 drop
arms
> to claimed they could only replace the ball joints while the arms were
still
> on the vehicle (by heating it up).  Having already been told by several
> people that is not the case I
> > took my business elsewhere.  I turns out my local VW FLAPS has welded up
a
> little jig specifically for the Type 2 ball joints.  As some of you have
> found out, the Type 2 ball joint has a flange that goes all the way to the
> edge of the control arm with the
> > exception of 2 notched areas so its hard to set it safely in the press.
> The VW shop's jig lets the control arm sit in those 2 notches while the
> press exerts pressure on the ball joint.  So today I will pick up my 2
lower
> control arms with new ball joints
> > and only pay $30 labor for the pair instead of the $125 each that the
tire
> store wanted to charge me for doing it on the vehicle.
> >
> > --
> > Larry
> > sonofed(-at-)karmannghia.org
> > www.fraternaltwins.homestead.com
> > Oo\ /oO
> >
> >
> ></pre>


